    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "can u elaborate on the disincentive part? like, are there specific policies or types of benefits that are the main culprits for people dropping out of the workforce?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The main culprits are often \"benefit cliffs,\" where a single job offer causes benefits like unemployment insurance or housing vouchers to vanish instantly, making the net income from working lower than staying on the safety net. Specific policies such as the Earned Income Tax Credit (EITC) are actually designed to counteract this by providing a bonus that increases as earnings rise, thereby encouraging work. Conversely, rigid welfare systems with high cash benefits and low eligibility thresholds tend to create the strongest disincentives for low-skilled individuals to enter or remain in the workforce.",
      "source": "target",
